5. Project Structure

vbcua/
├── app.py                          # Streamlit UI — Home → Upload → Result → History pages
├── config.py                       # Central settings (models, thresholds, scoring weights)
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
├── .streamlit/
│   └── config.toml                 # UI theme configuration
├── data/
│   ├── reference_concepts.json     # Reference explanations + key points per concept
│   └── sessions.db                 # SQLite DB (auto-created on first run)
├── modules/                        # Core Intelligence Layer
│   ├── speech_to_text.py           # Whisper wrapper
│   ├── semantic_understanding.py   # Sentence-BERT similarity + key-point coverage
│   ├── filler_analysis.py          # NLTK-based filler word detection
│   ├── audio_features.py           # Librosa: pauses, RMS energy, waveform plot
│   ├── scoring.py                  # Similarity Score, Speech Score, Final Score, Confidence
│   └── report_generator.py         # ReportLab PDF report (+ optional Gemini summary)
├── utils/
│   ├── storage.py                  # SQLite persistence for session history
│   └── helpers.py                  # File handling, SoundFile-based audio validation
├── assets/                         # Auto-generated waveform images
└── tests/
    ├── conftest.py                 # Stubs heavy deps for fast unit testing
    ├── test_filler_analysis.py
    └── test_scoring.py


6. Setup & Installation

bash# 1. Navigate to the project folder
cd vbcua

# 2. (Recommended) Create a virtual environment
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate        # Windows
source venv/bin/activate     # macOS/Linux

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 4. Install FFmpeg (required by Whisper for audio decoding) and add it to your system PATH
#    Download: https://www.gyan.dev/ffmpeg/builds/


First run downloads the Whisper model (~140MB) and Sentence-BERT model (~80MB) from
Hugging Face — an internet connection is needed the first time only.



Optional — enable AI-generated qualitative summaries in the PDF report:

bashexport GEMINI_API_KEY="your-key-here"     # Windows: set GEMINI_API_KEY=your-key-here

Without this, the report still works fully — it falls back to a rule-based summary.


7. Running the Application

bashstreamlit run app.py

Open the local URL Streamlit prints (usually http://localhost:8501).

Usage flow:


Home — click Start
Upload & Analyze — select a concept, upload or record your spoken explanation, play it back to confirm, click Analyze
Result — view transcript, Similarity/Speech/Final scores, waveform, confidence level, and feedback
Click Generate PDF Report, then Download PDF Report
History tab shows all past evaluations



8. Testing

bashpytest tests/ -v

tests/conftest.py stubs out torch/whisper/sentence-transformers/librosa so the pure-logic
tests (scoring math, filler word detection) run in under 2 seconds without model downloads.
7 tests currently pass, covering:


Filler word detection accuracy and ratio calculation
Scoring classification (Strong/Moderate/Poor) at both ends of the spectrum
Feedback generation for missed key concepts


The full pipeline (Whisper → Sentence-BERT → Librosa → scoring → PDF) is exercised end-to-end
by running the Streamlit app itself.


9. Scoring Methodology

The Final Score (0–100) is a weighted blend:

ComponentWeightMeasuresSemantic similarity55%Cosine similarity (Sentence-BERT) between the explanation and reference concept, blended 70/30 with key-point coverageFiller word score15%Penalizes high "um/like/you know" ratioPause score15%Penalizes excessive silent gapsEnergy consistency15%Rewards steady speaking volume

Classification thresholds:


Strong Understanding: ≥ 75
Moderate Understanding: 50–74
Poor Understanding: < 50


Confidence level (High/Medium/Low) is derived separately from voice energy consistency.


10. Known Issues / Limitations

#IssueStatus / Workaround1Requires FFmpeg installed separately for mp3/m4a decodingDocumented above; OS-specific installer, not bundled2Whisper "base" model favors speed over accuracy on CPUSwitch to "small"/"medium" in config.py if more compute is available3Limited to 5 pre-defined reference conceptsExtendable via data/reference_concepts.json, no code changes needed4No multi-user authenticationOut of scope; single-user local session by design5First run needs internet to download AI models (~220MB)One-time only; fully offline afterward


11. Future Enhancements


Support for additional languages (multilingual Whisper models + translated reference concepts)
User accounts and per-user history
Deployment to a hosted platform (Streamlit Community Cloud / Render / Azure)
Expanded reference concept library covering more subjects
Real-time (streaming) transcription and scoring instead of post-recording analysis
